revenues and operating income were unchanged, interest charges rose steeply,
reflecting heavy capital investments.
Bombardier's aerospace interests include stakes in Short Brothers of
Northern Ireland, the US business jet maker Lear, and De Havilland, the
Toronto-based commuter aircraft maker.
Pre-tax losses from railway equipment narrowed to CDollars 23.9m from
CDollars 72.6m, with revenues growing slightly to CDollars 1.3bn.
The company predicted a 'slow recovery' in this segment in 1994-95,
attributed partly to the settlement reached with Eurotunnel last December.
